03:19.480 --> 03:21.681
Keep that ammo out back
with the .50 Cal.

03:21.716 --> 03:22.916
3rd Mass. Comes in hot,

03:22.951 --> 03:25.085
Skitters and Mechs
can't be far behind.

03:25.120 --> 03:27.321
We're gonna have to be able
to move fast.

03:27.356 --> 03:31.325
Yeah, that's gonna be easier
for some than others.

03:31.360 --> 03:33.528
Sarah, right?

03:35.364 --> 03:37.632
Did Dr. Glass give you
any kind of E.T.A.?

03:37.667 --> 03:40.369
Yeah. Two days ago.
He's stubborn.

03:40.403 --> 03:42.738
So it's a boy.

03:42.773 --> 03:43.840
Don't know.

03:43.874 --> 03:45.542
Just didn't like calling him
an "it."

03:45.576 --> 03:46.910
All right.

03:46.944 --> 03:48.779
Well, let's hope that you can
hang on till after we move.

03:48.813 --> 03:49.847
Excuse me.

03:49.881 --> 03:52.349
Captain,
do you have any children?

03:55.287 --> 03:57.355
Two daughters.

03:58.724 --> 04:01.993
You better get in line
before the pot runs dry, mama.

04:05.031 --> 04:07.833
If this attack happens,
she's gonna have to keep up.

04:07.867 --> 04:10.669
Don't worry about her.
We'll do what we have to do.

04:10.704 --> 04:13.239
"We"?
What are you, her keeper?

04:13.273 --> 04:14.640
No.
I'm just pragmatic.

04:14.674 --> 04:16.976
Get in the chow line
with the pregnant lady,

04:17.010 --> 04:18.711
nobody even minds
if you ask for seconds.

04:29.255 --> 04:31.323
Used to <i>hate</i> eating
my vegetables.

04:31.357 --> 04:34.026
You won't hate these.
They're from our garden.

04:34.060 --> 04:35.861
And the zucchini
is amazing.

04:35.896 --> 04:38.597
Better than anything you had
at Central Square.

04:38.631 --> 04:40.633
Welcome back.
Any problems?

04:40.667 --> 04:43.068
No. Your friends
are on their way.

04:43.102 --> 04:45.037
And I didn't see any sign
of Skitters,

04:45.071 --> 04:47.072
so I made a detour.

04:47.107 --> 04:48.574
Apples.

04:48.608 --> 04:49.875
Clayton:
Fresh and ripe as can be.

04:49.910 --> 04:51.010
You go ahead,
help yourself.

04:51.045 --> 04:54.047
Pretty nice setup
you got here, Terry.

04:54.081 --> 04:55.582
You're settling in.

04:55.617 --> 04:58.419
You think
we're getting complacent?

04:58.454 --> 05:00.889
I've just gotten used
to packing light.

05:00.923 --> 05:03.492
Yeah, well, we're
pretty secluded up here.

05:03.526 --> 05:07.029
Like I said, the Skitters have
already swept the area, so...

05:07.063 --> 05:08.864
And if we did
have to jump,

05:08.898 --> 05:11.267
we could still hit
the ground running.

05:11.301 --> 05:13.402
Hey, dad, try some?

05:13.436 --> 05:15.537
Mm-hmm.

05:15.572 --> 05:17.805
[ Slurps,
exhales sharply ]

05:17.840 --> 05:19.841
How does she do that?
How do you do that?
[ Chuckles ]

05:19.875 --> 05:21.576
It's great, Hon.
Thanks.

05:21.610 --> 05:24.144
Terry, you needed a hand
with that generator?

05:24.179 --> 05:26.012
You got it.

05:26.047 --> 05:27.314
This goes in here?

05:27.348 --> 05:29.316
Yeah, that's good.
Thanks.

05:43.797 --> 05:46.431
[ Door opens ]

05:46.466 --> 05:49.301
I smell asparagus,

05:49.335 --> 05:51.870
which means
you're boiling it,

05:51.905 --> 05:54.473
which means
you're ruining it.

05:56.109 --> 05:57.843
We'll pass that on
to the chef.

05:57.878 --> 06:03.115
Kudos, once again,
for the information.

06:03.149 --> 06:06.252
2nd Mass. was <i>exactly</i> where
you said it was gonna be.

06:06.286 --> 06:09.188
It wasn't exactly
voluntary.

06:09.223 --> 06:10.990
And like I said, this doesn't
have to be this way.

06:11.025 --> 06:12.291
Mm.

06:12.326 --> 06:14.194
So, what is this,
my last chance to convert?

06:14.228 --> 06:15.562
Maybe.

06:15.596 --> 06:16.830
You must have done

06:16.864 --> 06:18.365
one hell of a Tony Robbins
on those people

06:18.399 --> 06:20.033
to get them
to hand over their kids.

06:20.067 --> 06:22.503
I <i>served</i>
<i>with those people.</i>

06:22.537 --> 06:24.071
Weaver's always been
by the book,

06:24.105 --> 06:25.639
so new orders
from Colonel Porter

06:25.673 --> 06:27.474
were enough for him,

06:27.509 --> 06:29.710
and, uh, his second-in-command, um...
Mason.

06:29.745 --> 06:33.081
It's pretty clear he'd do
anything to protect his boys.

06:34.817 --> 06:38.987
You really think you can deal
with those lizards?

06:44.060 --> 06:47.529
It's not about winning or losing
anymore, Pope.

06:47.564 --> 06:48.964
It's about surviving.

06:48.998 --> 06:51.600
Yeah, where does that
leave you and me?

06:51.635 --> 06:53.736
Right where we were

06:53.771 --> 06:55.572
after you broke
into our supply shed.

06:55.606 --> 06:59.476
Well, to be fair,
it was unlocked.

06:59.510 --> 07:01.445
Yeah, because
you stabbed his brother,

07:01.479 --> 07:03.347
who was supposed
to be guarding it.

07:05.049 --> 07:07.351
You're making a big mistake,
Clayton!

07:07.386 --> 07:09.319
I really am
one hell of a cook!

07:09.353 --> 07:11.521
Oh, I don't doubt that!

07:11.556 --> 07:13.323
Bye, Pope!

07:13.357 --> 07:14.490
[ Door closes ]

07:14.525 --> 07:15.858
Pretty handy
with a mop, too.

07:15.892 --> 07:17.159
This place
could use one.

07:17.194 --> 07:19.662
It's covered
in broken glass.

07:31.742 --> 07:33.142
[ Spits ]

07:55.430 --> 07:57.531
Looks like these two
won't make it back

07:57.565 --> 07:59.099
to the 2nd Mass.
Anytime soon.

07:59.133 --> 08:00.199
[ Flies buzzing ]

08:00.234 --> 08:02.201
Civilization --

08:02.236 --> 08:04.237
you got to love it.

08:09.009 --> 08:10.677
Captain.

08:10.711 --> 08:13.146
The conditions of these bikes
is a disgrace.

08:13.180 --> 08:15.783
Is that right?
I'll have to look into that.

08:15.817 --> 08:18.152
Which ones of these
are gassed up?

08:18.186 --> 08:20.255
[ Sighs ]
Those two are good to go.

08:22.191 --> 08:25.393
I don't remember you
being assigned to patrol.

08:25.428 --> 08:26.794
That's right.
You're assigning me now.

08:26.829 --> 08:29.263
We have fighters for that.

08:29.297 --> 08:30.931
We have Dai --
Dai can come with me.

08:30.965 --> 08:31.932
It's been 48 hours.

08:31.966 --> 08:33.567
There's been no sign
of the Skitters,

08:33.601 --> 08:34.900
no sign of the 3rd.

08:34.934 --> 08:36.736
At the very least, the escorts
should be back by now.

08:36.770 --> 08:39.205
So they were delayed.
It happens in war.

08:39.239 --> 08:40.640
That's not good enough.

08:40.674 --> 08:43.576
Clayton said he's taking
the kids to Westminster.

08:43.610 --> 08:44.777
It's a half a day's walk.

08:44.811 --> 08:46.578
We can do that
in a couple of hours.

08:46.613 --> 08:48.047
We'll go.
We'll check it out.

08:48.081 --> 08:49.682
If it's all fine,
we'll come back.

08:49.716 --> 08:52.084
What happens if the Skitters
attack while you're gone?

08:52.119 --> 08:53.819
What if they come
after <i>you?</i>

08:53.854 --> 08:56.155
You're not just another civvy,
you know.

08:57.557 --> 08:59.291
I could order you to say!
[ Engine turns over ]

08:59.326 --> 09:00.359
You could.

09:00.393 --> 09:01.861
[ Engine revs ]
Tom!

09:01.895 --> 09:06.598
Whatever happens,
I want you and Dai back.

09:06.633 --> 09:07.766
Understood?

09:07.800 --> 09:10.736
[ Engines rev ]

09:14.492 --> 09:15.993
2 miles.
No sign of Pope.

09:16.498 --> 09:17.866
Think he's gonna
try anything?

09:17.900 --> 09:19.667
No. Pope could have
killed you.

09:19.702 --> 09:22.036
And coming after us
buys him nothing.

09:22.071 --> 09:23.504
How long are we
gonna keep this up?

09:23.538 --> 09:25.372
Look, it's a lot easier
on everybody

09:25.407 --> 09:27.341
if they want to be here.

09:27.375 --> 09:29.909
Next exchange is tomorrow.
We'll see after that.

09:32.046 --> 09:35.048
Hal: Eating vegetables
like a champion.

09:35.082 --> 09:37.484
Thought I heard some commotion
out there.

09:37.518 --> 09:39.286
One of the sentries
thought he saw a coyote.

09:39.320 --> 09:40.420
Mike:
You definitely have

09:40.455 --> 09:41.955
a different scale of problems
out here.

09:41.990 --> 09:45.593
[ Chuckles ] You get used to it
after a while.

09:45.628 --> 09:48.430
What's the matter, Rick,
not hungry?

09:52.268 --> 09:54.002
Tell you what
[Clears throat]

09:54.037 --> 09:56.872
When your old man and I
were posted together,

09:56.907 --> 09:59.241
he could not stop
talking about you.

09:59.275 --> 10:02.177
Don't worry.
Mostly good stuff.

10:04.080 --> 10:07.082
And what good stuff
could that be?

10:07.116 --> 10:09.685
How I was sick
all the time?

10:09.719 --> 10:12.654
How I could
barely catch my breath?

10:16.726 --> 10:18.326
[ Utensils slam ]

10:20.096 --> 10:21.930
How can you eat
their food?

10:21.964 --> 10:24.933
Excuse me?

10:35.612 --> 10:38.781
We are <i>guests</i> here, Rick.

10:38.815 --> 10:41.483
I raised you better
than that.

10:41.518 --> 10:43.886
Excuse my son's manners.

10:48.692 --> 10:50.894
You get a pass
on chores tonight --

10:50.928 --> 10:52.929
since you're new here.

10:52.964 --> 10:56.100
[ Scoffs lightly ]
You don't have to do that.

10:56.134 --> 10:58.769
[ Mockingly ]
"Since you're new here."

11:25.730 --> 11:28.698
[ Insects chirping ]

11:28.732 --> 11:31.334
[ Owl hoots ]

11:44.314 --> 11:45.781
What do you see
out there?

11:45.816 --> 11:49.285
I don't know.
Stars.

11:49.319 --> 11:51.654
And captain kick-ass
up there.

11:51.688 --> 11:53.322
[ Both chuckle ]

11:53.356 --> 11:55.023
I mean,
I know you guys think

11:55.058 --> 11:56.892
you're off the Skitter radar
and everything,

11:56.926 --> 11:59.294
but shouldn't there at least
be patrols or...

11:59.328 --> 12:01.062
Aren't <i>you</i> the soldier?

12:01.097 --> 12:03.831
[ Chuckles ]

12:03.865 --> 12:06.733
Chip off the old block.

12:06.768 --> 12:09.102
Then your father,
he's still...

12:09.136 --> 12:11.271
Alive. Yes.

12:11.305 --> 12:12.639
Yes.

12:12.673 --> 12:14.674
Um...

12:14.709 --> 12:17.477
I was just thinking
about how this is the first time

12:17.512 --> 12:19.513
we've been apart
since the attack.

12:24.653 --> 12:27.456
But you like it here,
don't you?

12:27.490 --> 12:29.892
Yeah.

12:31.128 --> 12:32.395
Lourdes: Hal.

12:32.429 --> 12:34.397
I mean, it's nice.

12:35.499 --> 12:37.099
[ Door closes ]

12:38.434 --> 12:41.436
I'm sorry.
I'll catch up with you later.

12:43.106 --> 12:44.206
I knew I'd seen it.

12:44.240 --> 12:45.840
Eli Russell
was wearing it

12:45.875 --> 12:47.909
when his father
robbed the clinic.

12:49.011 --> 12:51.612
I was there when Clayton
let the Russells run.

12:51.646 --> 12:53.580
Maybe the kid dropped it.

12:55.216 --> 12:57.118
[ Sighs ]
What?

12:57.152 --> 12:59.320
Okay,
it's probably nothing,

12:59.354 --> 13:00.989
but they've got sentries
posted on the house,

13:01.023 --> 13:02.891
and the barn's
locked up tight.

13:02.925 --> 13:04.025
So?

13:04.060 --> 13:06.261
Nobody's watching the sky
or the road.

13:06.295 --> 13:08.130
I mean,
it actually feels like

13:08.164 --> 13:10.433
they're more interested
in watching us.

13:10.467 --> 13:12.001
Or maybe not.

13:12.036 --> 13:14.170
Look,
I've known Terry Clayton

13:14.204 --> 13:16.139
since a week
after the attack.

13:16.173 --> 13:18.307
It's gonna take more
than a backpack and looks

13:18.341 --> 13:21.176
to convince me this is anything
except what he says.

13:21.210 --> 13:24.213
Round up the others.
Get them to bed.

13:24.247 --> 13:27.783
I guarantee this will look
better by morning.

13:27.817 --> 13:28.817
Yeah.

13:36.792 --> 13:39.794
[ Sighs ]

14:07.192 --> 14:09.460
[ Breathing shakily ]

14:38.925 --> 14:40.459
[ Gun cocks ]

14:42.762 --> 14:45.062
I always liked you, Mike.

14:45.097 --> 14:48.099
That's why I'm gonna talk
and you're gonna listen.

14:52.003 --> 14:53.570
[ Gun uncocks ]

15:01.545 --> 15:03.614
Eli Russell.

15:03.648 --> 15:06.616
Short answer?
He was here.

15:06.650 --> 15:08.618
What's the long answer?

15:11.556 --> 15:14.592
I can't even begin to tell you
what it was like

15:14.626 --> 15:16.127
when the 7th went down.

15:16.161 --> 15:19.164
Skitters came after us
like locusts.

15:19.198 --> 15:21.499
They tore us to pieces.

15:21.534 --> 15:24.469
We're the only ones
who survived the raid,

15:24.504 --> 15:26.472
and the Skitters
were still hot on us.

15:26.506 --> 15:28.841
I mean, we'd retreat,
defend, retreat, defend,

15:28.876 --> 15:32.145
and they still
kept coming.

15:32.180 --> 15:34.614
We had a little young girl
with us -- Megan.

15:34.648 --> 15:35.748
She fell behind.

15:35.783 --> 15:38.117
Didn't realize it
until it was too late.

15:38.152 --> 15:39.752
Skitters got her.

15:39.786 --> 15:43.789
And we just kept retreating
to save the group.

15:43.823 --> 15:45.790
And then they stopped.

15:45.825 --> 15:47.759
They stayed away
for a week.

15:47.793 --> 15:50.862
It's almost like they were
saying, "Okay, thanks."

15:50.896 --> 15:53.264
Thanks for <i>what?</i>

15:53.299 --> 15:55.066
For not attacking
when they had Megan,

15:55.101 --> 15:56.235
for letting them keep her.

15:56.269 --> 15:57.369
That's what they figured.

15:57.404 --> 16:01.140
So Megan found us here
a while later.

16:01.175 --> 16:02.308
She'd been harnessed,

16:02.343 --> 16:04.010
but she also had a message
from the Skitter

16:04.044 --> 16:06.513
who was in charge
of her group.

16:06.548 --> 16:08.282
All they wanted
were the kids.

16:08.316 --> 16:10.885
A Skitter told you this?

16:10.919 --> 16:12.687
Through Megan. Yeah.

16:12.721 --> 16:14.923
Mike, they didn't want to die
any more than we do,

16:14.957 --> 16:16.557
but they have
their missions, too.

16:16.592 --> 16:18.526
It sounds crazy,
but it's like every group

16:18.560 --> 16:20.194
has to hit their numbers.

16:20.229 --> 16:21.596
Once we understood that,

16:21.630 --> 16:24.265
once we knew what they wanted
and what they didn't want,

16:24.300 --> 16:25.900
the arrangement...

16:25.934 --> 16:28.035
Just evolved.

16:28.069 --> 16:31.072
You've been trading kids
to the Skitters?

16:31.106 --> 16:34.876
In return for immunity
for my men and their families.

16:34.910 --> 16:38.046
That's why I went after
the 2nd Mass.

16:40.182 --> 16:43.785
So the 3rd Mass.,
on the run,

16:43.819 --> 16:46.020
Porter's orders...

16:46.054 --> 16:48.489
It was all a lie.
Yeah.

16:52.862 --> 16:55.763
I need to know
what you're thinking, Mike.

16:55.798 --> 16:57.832
What <i>should</i>
<i>I be thinking?</i>

17:00.869 --> 17:03.871
That this is
a messed-up world

17:03.906 --> 17:05.172
and this is all we have.

17:05.207 --> 17:07.141
And I know
that you understand that,

17:07.175 --> 17:09.377
and that's why I asked you
to come along.

17:09.411 --> 17:12.179
And if I say no?

17:15.451 --> 17:18.686
This is not just about
your survival anymore.

17:18.721 --> 17:21.223
You got to think
about Rick.

17:27.765 --> 17:29.533
Mike...

17:38.971 --> 17:40.105
Okay, everyone,

17:40.139 --> 17:41.406
I'll let you know when
to break out the cigars.

17:41.657 --> 17:43.191
And I know you got
better things to do.

17:43.226 --> 17:45.293
Let's go.

17:45.327 --> 17:47.595
No, Margaret,
please, stay.

17:47.629 --> 17:48.896
All right.

17:48.931 --> 17:51.198
As long as I don't have
to say "Push, push."

17:51.233 --> 17:52.866
Oh, my God. Is it supposed
to feel like this?

17:52.901 --> 17:54.401
It's okay.
It's just a contraction.

17:54.435 --> 17:55.602
[ Moaning ]
There you go.

17:55.637 --> 17:56.670
And breathe.

17:56.704 --> 17:59.373
You got a name
picked out?

17:59.407 --> 18:01.141
If it's a boy,
I was thinking "David."

18:01.175 --> 18:02.843
Is that
the baby's father?

18:02.877 --> 18:04.745
No, that would be
sperm donor.

18:04.779 --> 18:07.481
Yeah, dad's not
in the picture.

18:07.515 --> 18:09.349
I was a work-at-home
interior designer.

18:09.384 --> 18:11.552
Figured I could be
a work-at-home single mom, too.

18:11.586 --> 18:12.886
My timing always sucked.

18:12.921 --> 18:14.221
What do you mean?

18:14.255 --> 18:16.089
I had it all planned out.

18:16.123 --> 18:18.025
I was gonna do meetings
on Skype.

18:18.059 --> 18:21.062
I'd already joined a play group
with other working moms.

18:21.096 --> 18:23.197
Then, six weeks
after I got pregnant,

18:23.231 --> 18:24.665
aliens invaded the planet.

18:26.902 --> 18:28.703
All right,
let's take a look.

18:28.737 --> 18:30.171
Here you go.
Bring your knees up.

18:30.205 --> 18:32.139
[ Gasping ]
All right. All right.

18:32.174 --> 18:34.542
All right. We're just gonna take a look.
That's good.

18:39.981 --> 18:42.483
I wish
you'd known him before.

18:42.517 --> 18:45.886
Sick as he was,
I never heard him complain.

18:45.921 --> 18:47.888
Not once.

18:50.325 --> 18:52.927
[ Chuckling ] And, lord,
he could make me laugh.

19:02.172 --> 19:04.874
I hated it
when he was taken.

19:07.178 --> 19:10.915
But I hate what they did
to him even more.

19:13.118 --> 19:15.652
Mike, what's going on?

19:15.687 --> 19:17.420
Hal?

19:17.455 --> 19:18.688
Grab your weapon.
Gather the others.

19:18.723 --> 19:19.822
We're leaving
this place now.

19:19.857 --> 19:21.958
Clayton's made a deal
with the Skitters.

19:21.992 --> 19:24.027
Hey, Rick, come on!

19:24.061 --> 19:25.055
We got to get up, buddy.
We got to go.

19:25.056 --> 19:25.961
Got to go --
put your shoes on.

19:25.963 --> 19:27.497
We need to get out of here.
Get up.

19:32.902 --> 19:34.936
Hal?
What are you doing?

19:37.673 --> 19:39.574
Clayton made a deal
with the Skitters.

19:39.608 --> 19:41.709
Tell me you don't know
about this.

19:41.744 --> 19:44.046
I-I was gonna talk to them
about you,

19:44.080 --> 19:45.914
fix it
so that you could stay.

19:48.718 --> 19:50.352
Go. Go.

19:50.386 --> 19:52.120
They're never gonna let you leave!
Go, go, go, go, go go, go, go!

19:52.155 --> 19:53.588
Dad! Dad!!

19:53.623 --> 19:54.656
No -- no time!
Got to go!

19:54.690 --> 19:56.524
Dad, wake up!
They're leaving!

19:56.559 --> 19:58.493
Get up, dad!
They're leaving!

19:58.528 --> 20:00.595
The kids
are getting away!

20:00.630 --> 20:03.398
Go, go, go, go.

20:03.433 --> 20:05.900
Come on! Come on!
Go, go, go!

20:18.213 --> 20:20.380
They're going around
this way!

20:20.415 --> 20:22.448
Clayton:
Move, move, move!

20:22.483 --> 20:26.452
All right,
we need the little ones alive!

20:26.486 --> 20:27.787
Go, go, go, go, go, go!

20:27.821 --> 20:30.255
[ Gunshots ]

20:35.829 --> 20:37.797
Back here. Stay down.
Down!

20:44.538 --> 20:46.505
Come on. Go. Go.

20:46.540 --> 20:48.207
I swear to God,
I'll kill the next man I see!

20:50.010 --> 20:51.710
[ Machine-gun fire ]

20:56.416 --> 20:58.150
Mike, come on!

21:02.356 --> 21:04.023
[ Panting ]

21:04.057 --> 21:06.526
I got this.
You two keep going.

21:06.560 --> 21:07.961
You can't out-shoot
all those guys.

21:07.995 --> 21:09.229
I can try for a while.

21:09.263 --> 21:10.663
[ Machine-gun fire continues ]

21:10.698 --> 21:12.698
You just got to promise me
you take care of Rick.

21:15.869 --> 21:17.570
Keep him busy.

21:19.039 --> 21:21.608
[ Machine-gun fire continues ]

21:21.642 --> 21:22.909
Okay.

21:25.979 --> 21:29.415
Listen, Ricky,
no matter what happens,

21:29.450 --> 21:31.350
I love you, always.

21:31.385 --> 21:32.518
You hear me?

21:32.553 --> 21:35.355
But you got to go.
You got to run.

21:37.191 --> 21:39.226
You stay with Hal.

21:39.260 --> 21:41.094
I'll see you soon.

21:41.129 --> 21:42.229
Go.

21:42.263 --> 21:43.831
Go!

21:53.910 --> 21:55.510
Line in the sand,
is that it?!

21:57.179 --> 21:59.314
Or maybe you think you're
just somehow better than us!

21:59.348 --> 22:01.884
They harnessed my son!

22:01.918 --> 22:04.486
I know what they're doing
to these children!

22:04.521 --> 22:08.424
Maybe I can't stop it,

22:08.458 --> 22:11.694
but I sure as hell
won't be a part of it!

22:19.703 --> 22:21.270
[ Gun cocks ]

22:22.772 --> 22:25.308
The world's coming apart,
Mike.

22:30.614 --> 22:31.847
[ All panting ]

22:31.882 --> 22:33.316
[ Gunshot ]

22:39.490 --> 22:42.492
Come on. Come on.
Let's go. Let's go.

22:45.145 --> 22:46.345
[ Engine revving ]

22:46.356 --> 22:48.157
[ Engine shuts off ]
Man: All right,
I'll let him know.

22:48.192 --> 22:49.792
[ Dog barking ]

22:49.826 --> 22:51.894
[ Indistinct talking ]

22:52.825 --> 22:53.925
About time.
What'd you find?

22:53.960 --> 22:55.093
Nothing.

22:55.128 --> 22:56.261
This map is wrong.

22:56.296 --> 22:57.329
What are you
talking about?

22:57.364 --> 22:58.330
Oh, it's rural,
all right,

22:58.365 --> 22:59.798
but we didn't see anything
even close

22:59.832 --> 23:01.333
to Clayton's Sanctuary.

23:01.368 --> 23:03.435
Still no sign of the 3rd?
No.

23:03.470 --> 23:05.371
- Escorts aren't back yet?
- No, still not back.

23:05.405 --> 23:07.573
Damn it.

23:07.608 --> 23:09.608
Clayton had no reason
to lie to us.

23:09.643 --> 23:11.410
Then why is not one thing
he told us is holding up?

23:11.445 --> 23:12.678
We need to organize
search teams.

23:12.713 --> 23:14.547
- Kids on foot couldn't have gone that far.
- No way.

23:14.582 --> 23:16.616
Our orders are clear.
We're to hold this position.

23:16.650 --> 23:18.685
Orders relayed to us by a guy
that we barely know!

23:18.719 --> 23:20.721
In a dicey situation
where we don't have clue one

23:20.755 --> 23:22.390
about what might have
really happened!

23:22.424 --> 23:24.492
You know
something's not right!

23:24.527 --> 23:25.594
All I know
is what I've been <i>told.</i>

23:25.628 --> 23:26.795
We wait!

23:26.829 --> 23:28.664
<i>You</i> wait.
I'm going back out.

23:28.698 --> 23:30.366
It'll be daylight soon.

23:34.772 --> 23:36.506
[ Birds chirping ]

23:36.540 --> 23:38.442
Hal: I haven't heard anything
in a while.

23:38.476 --> 23:39.676
Maybe we lost them.

23:39.710 --> 23:42.980
Lourdes: It's still a long way
back to the school.

23:46.885 --> 23:49.687
What do you think?

23:49.721 --> 23:52.356
They're about
to fall over.

23:52.390 --> 23:55.526
Better it happens inside
than out.

23:55.560 --> 23:57.061
Let's go this way.

24:01.333 --> 24:04.468
How's Mike
gonna find us?

24:04.502 --> 24:06.170
He told us
to keep moving.

24:06.204 --> 24:08.439
He's gonna try to catch up,
all right?

24:08.473 --> 24:10.141
[ Sighs ] Okay.

24:10.175 --> 24:11.408
All right, everybody.

24:11.443 --> 24:13.477
We're gonna hole up here
for a couple of hours.

24:13.512 --> 24:14.846
Then we're gonna
move out.

24:18.883 --> 24:21.051
The rest of the kids
are up in the bedrooms,

24:21.086 --> 24:22.586
and they're
already asleep.

24:33.864 --> 24:36.032
You play?

24:36.066 --> 24:39.335
It's been a while.

24:39.369 --> 24:42.938
This was always
one of my favorites.

24:48.311 --> 24:52.847
[ "Once in Royal David's City"
plays ]

25:15.837 --> 25:18.038
[ Music continues ]

25:38.460 --> 25:40.828
[ Music continues ]

25:43.297 --> 25:45.799
Think they'll find us?

25:45.833 --> 25:47.867
They'll try.

25:47.901 --> 25:49.435
You should get
some sleep.

25:49.469 --> 25:50.502
I'm not tired.

25:52.539 --> 25:54.973
I should go ahead,
try and get help.

25:55.008 --> 25:56.909
No. No.
We're staying together.

25:56.943 --> 25:57.910
We get
a couple hours' sleep,

25:57.944 --> 25:58.944
and then
we're gonna head out.

25:58.978 --> 26:00.412
They're exhausted.

26:00.446 --> 26:02.781
You're exhausted.

26:02.815 --> 26:05.617
I can move faster
on my own.

26:05.652 --> 26:06.618
Let me do this.

26:06.653 --> 26:08.887
Are you sure
that's a good idea?

26:08.922 --> 26:11.290
Why wouldn't it be?

26:11.324 --> 26:13.892
What if you get lost...

26:13.927 --> 26:15.628
Or you just keep going?

26:15.662 --> 26:17.296
Keep going where?

26:17.330 --> 26:19.331
Someplace safer.

26:19.366 --> 26:21.500
The only place
he's going...

26:21.534 --> 26:22.867
Is the school.

26:22.902 --> 26:24.569
And he's right.

26:24.603 --> 26:26.404
We need the help.

26:28.807 --> 26:30.274
[ Sighs ]

26:33.178 --> 26:35.012
You go to that highway,
and you follow it.

26:35.046 --> 26:36.614
You stay off road
as much as you can.

26:36.649 --> 26:39.184
If you see or hear anybody,
you run.

26:39.218 --> 26:41.186
You run all the way back
to the school.

26:41.220 --> 26:43.222
Okay. All right.

26:44.424 --> 26:45.791
Hal...

26:45.825 --> 26:48.727
I, um...

26:48.762 --> 26:50.396
I never said
thanks for --

26:50.430 --> 26:52.198
for getting me
from the Skitters.

26:52.233 --> 26:54.800
You're welcome.

26:58.337 --> 26:59.471
You math geek.

26:59.505 --> 27:01.005
[ Chuckles ]

27:01.040 --> 27:02.940
Dumb jock.

27:02.975 --> 27:04.609
[ Sighs ]

27:24.228 --> 27:26.161
[ Indistinct talking
in distance ]

27:30.634 --> 27:32.735
Greene: They must have got
on the road here.

27:32.769 --> 27:35.238
Clayton: All right, they can't
be traveling too fast

27:35.272 --> 27:37.006
with the little ones
tagging along.

27:37.040 --> 27:38.508
So let's keep
our eyes open!

27:38.542 --> 27:40.844
Man: I'll try.

27:47.384 --> 27:50.653
It's been hours.
Why isn't the baby moving?

27:50.687 --> 27:52.955
[ Moans ]

27:55.025 --> 27:58.327
I was afraid of this.
Your baby is breech.

27:58.361 --> 28:01.697
"Breech" meaning...

28:01.732 --> 28:03.933
Well, his head is way up here
instead of facing down.

28:03.968 --> 28:05.268
Baby can't move
into the birth canal.

28:05.303 --> 28:08.171
Is he okay?

28:08.206 --> 28:10.541
Well, we need to get him
turned around.

28:10.575 --> 28:14.244
And if you can't, what,
you'll do a C-section, right?

28:14.279 --> 28:17.448
I'm not an OB/GYN,
and I'm not a surgeon.

28:17.482 --> 28:19.950
You de-harnessed
those kids.

28:19.985 --> 28:21.118
Yeah, with a blowtorch.

28:21.153 --> 28:23.053
Dr. Glass.

28:27.725 --> 28:30.427
Is she gonna be able to move
if we have to?

28:30.461 --> 28:31.494
I don't know.

28:31.529 --> 28:32.862
Her baby's breech,

28:32.897 --> 28:35.832
and I would hate to try
a C-section here.

28:35.867 --> 28:37.634
Breech?

28:42.741 --> 28:44.075
Hello.

28:47.580 --> 28:50.049
My first daughter
was a breech baby.

28:50.083 --> 28:51.484
You're going to help?

28:51.518 --> 28:53.185
When my daughter was born,

28:53.220 --> 28:56.455
I helped the doula turn the baby
from the outside.

28:56.489 --> 28:59.624
You assisted in
an external cephalic version?

28:59.659 --> 29:02.094
I never knew
what they called it,

29:02.129 --> 29:04.163
but my wife and I
did a home birth.

29:04.197 --> 29:07.966
You know, people think
that soldiers are brave,

29:08.001 --> 29:10.636
but, uh, I'll take combat
over childbirth any day.

29:10.670 --> 29:12.238
You ready to try this?

29:12.272 --> 29:14.273
Yeah.

29:15.776 --> 29:16.843
Right.

29:16.877 --> 29:18.912
Doctor, shall we?

29:20.982 --> 29:23.284
Anne:
Let's get to work.

29:23.318 --> 29:26.754
[ Groans softly ]

29:26.788 --> 29:28.789
[ Engines revving ]

29:39.969 --> 29:41.270
[ Engines shut off ]

29:41.304 --> 29:42.270
How far out are we?

29:42.305 --> 29:43.505
Far.

29:43.539 --> 29:47.876
If this war is coming,
it's taking its sweet time.

29:47.910 --> 29:49.544
That looks like Ben.

29:49.579 --> 29:50.879
Ben!

29:50.913 --> 29:52.747
Ben: Dad!

29:52.781 --> 29:54.082
Where's Hal and Matt?!

29:54.116 --> 29:55.183
They're with the others,

29:55.218 --> 29:56.351
but they don't know
Clayton's coming!

29:56.386 --> 29:57.653
They're not
at the sanctuary.

29:57.687 --> 29:59.288
No, no, no. Mike said
it wasn't safe, so we left.

29:59.322 --> 30:00.422
They started
shooting at us!

30:00.456 --> 30:01.890
Who was shooting at you --
Clayton?

30:01.924 --> 30:03.692
Dad...

30:03.726 --> 30:05.794
I think Mike's dead.

30:05.828 --> 30:08.263
Is anybody else hurt?

30:08.298 --> 30:09.698
I-I don't know.

30:09.733 --> 30:10.966
Okay. You're okay.

30:11.000 --> 30:12.134
Dai's gonna
take you back,

30:12.168 --> 30:13.836
but first I need you
to tell me everything.

30:22.400 --> 30:23.379
G-4.

30:23.380 --> 30:24.347
Ah. Psych.

30:24.381 --> 30:26.249
Not even close.

30:26.283 --> 30:29.786
Hey.
What are you looking at?

30:29.820 --> 30:31.854
I'm waiting.

30:36.225 --> 30:38.326
You're worried
about Ben.

30:38.360 --> 30:40.795
I'm worried
about all of them.

30:40.829 --> 30:43.030
This must be
what my dad goes through,

30:43.065 --> 30:46.200
except for he's a lot better
at dealing with it than I am.

30:46.235 --> 30:48.169
No way!
You sunk my battleship.

30:48.203 --> 30:49.203
Guys!

30:49.238 --> 30:50.605
Hey, pack that up,
all right?

30:50.639 --> 30:52.173
We got to hit
the road here soon.

30:52.208 --> 30:54.876
Kind of like the old days,
you know.

30:54.910 --> 30:57.012
Eating
in the dining room...

30:57.046 --> 30:58.313
Board games.

30:58.347 --> 30:59.381
Yeah.

30:59.415 --> 31:01.884
Never had the patience
for them.

31:01.918 --> 31:05.521
Lacrosse, football --
that was my thing.

31:05.555 --> 31:08.624
Ever think
we'll have this again?

31:08.658 --> 31:10.893
Someday.

31:10.927 --> 31:13.462
You really think
we can beat them?

31:13.496 --> 31:15.931
Think we're gonna kick
their alien ass.

31:15.965 --> 31:18.000
Clayton: Good morning!

31:21.137 --> 31:22.671
They found us.
Quiet. Quiet.

31:22.705 --> 31:24.139
Come on out!
We're taking you home!

31:24.173 --> 31:25.841
Stay down.

31:28.578 --> 31:32.214
You know, I actually thought
of <i>buying</i> in this neighborhood

31:32.249 --> 31:33.415
once upon a time.

31:35.218 --> 31:37.286
Don't make me come in there
for you, Hal!

31:37.320 --> 31:39.989
Nobody wants to see
anybody else get hurt!

31:46.429 --> 31:48.530
We know about your deal!

31:48.565 --> 31:50.065
You need us alive!

31:50.100 --> 31:53.101
Yeah, well,
there's a term in war --

31:53.135 --> 31:54.836
"Acceptable losses."

31:56.205 --> 31:58.306
If one of your friends
gets hurt or killed,

31:58.340 --> 31:59.874
I can live with that.

31:59.909 --> 32:01.476
Can you?!

32:01.510 --> 32:02.543
Go to hell!

32:03.278 --> 32:04.712
Down!

32:04.747 --> 32:06.014
Get by the tree!

32:06.049 --> 32:08.251
Kid's armed, Clayton.
Not good.

32:11.789 --> 32:13.490
What are we
gonna do now?

32:13.524 --> 32:14.858
I'm gonna try
to hold them off.

32:14.893 --> 32:16.093
You take them out
the back.

32:16.127 --> 32:19.329
Take out the shooter,
and the rest will walk out.

32:19.364 --> 32:21.031
Man: All right.

32:21.066 --> 32:23.367
Got a line on him?

32:23.402 --> 32:25.569
Take your shot.

32:25.604 --> 32:27.038
[ Gunshot ]

32:28.874 --> 32:29.873
(Man #2) Behind you!

32:30.942 --> 32:33.910
Get your damn head
down, kid!

32:35.046 --> 32:36.980
Get around!

32:37.014 --> 32:38.214
Hey, Clayton!

32:38.249 --> 32:41.050
How's that Skitter deal
working now, huh?!

32:41.085 --> 32:42.451
Watch the house.

32:42.486 --> 32:44.354
Nail that son of a bitch!

32:44.388 --> 32:46.089
[ Gunfire ]

32:49.660 --> 32:51.560
Aah!

32:51.595 --> 32:53.462
Give it up, Pope!

32:53.497 --> 32:55.698
[ Gunfire ]

32:55.732 --> 32:57.433
Aah.

32:59.903 --> 33:01.737
Pull up a chair,
Professor.

33:01.772 --> 33:03.239
Put it down, Pope.

33:05.409 --> 33:07.610
No, I'm just
getting started.

33:07.644 --> 33:09.311
Trying to give your kids
a fighting chance.

33:09.346 --> 33:11.580
That doesn't explain
why you're here.

33:11.614 --> 33:13.949
It's complicated.

33:13.984 --> 33:16.084
I got <i>no</i> tolerance

33:16.119 --> 33:18.420
for anybody who gets into bed
with the Skitters.

33:22.958 --> 33:24.592
How many are down there?

33:24.626 --> 33:26.694
Got six or seven.

33:26.729 --> 33:28.429
Your whole tribe's
down there.

33:28.464 --> 33:31.966
Your oldest has a gun.

33:32.000 --> 33:33.601
They'll kill him
if it gets them the rest.

33:33.635 --> 33:35.102
That's too many of them.

33:35.137 --> 33:38.338
If we open up, we might get
lucky and get one or two.

33:38.373 --> 33:39.806
I'll take those odds.

33:39.841 --> 33:41.175
I won't.

33:41.209 --> 33:42.776
We get into a firefight,
we're not the only ones at risk.

33:42.811 --> 33:43.945
So what are you gonna do?

33:48.951 --> 33:50.485
Stop it.

33:52.054 --> 33:54.523
Hold your fire!

33:54.558 --> 33:56.025
Pope's dead!

33:56.059 --> 33:58.928
Clayton, it's Tom Mason!
I'm coming out!

33:58.963 --> 34:00.930
It's dad!

34:00.965 --> 34:02.298
Hey!

34:03.967 --> 34:07.270
Mason --
how'd he find us?

34:09.505 --> 34:12.175
We're not taking
any prisoners today, Mason!

34:12.208 --> 34:14.409
You might want to think
about that.

34:14.445 --> 34:15.545
Yeah?

34:15.579 --> 34:17.780
Everything you told us
is a lie.

34:17.813 --> 34:20.049
I know you haven't
talked to Porter,

34:20.083 --> 34:22.284
'cause I have,
and he's on his way.

34:24.187 --> 34:25.554
And you're gonna what?

34:25.589 --> 34:28.291
You're gonna offer yourself up
as a hostage.

34:28.326 --> 34:30.360
Is that it?
Why?

34:30.395 --> 34:32.362
I don't want them
to get hurt.

34:34.400 --> 34:35.434
Grab his weapon.

34:35.467 --> 34:37.168
What makes you think
he's telling the truth?

34:37.204 --> 34:38.771
'Cause Tom's smart enough
to understand

34:38.804 --> 34:40.206
that if I even suspect
he's lying,

34:40.239 --> 34:41.974
I'm gonna take it out
on his boys.

34:44.210 --> 34:45.844
All right, Tom,
you call them out!

34:48.349 --> 34:51.684
Hal, Matt, come on out!
It's all over!

34:51.719 --> 34:53.553
Everybody, come on out!

34:53.587 --> 34:55.721
[ Exhales sharply ]

35:14.707 --> 35:16.808
Matt: Dad!

35:19.045 --> 35:21.046
Dad, what'd you do?

35:21.080 --> 35:22.681
You would have kept fighting,
and they would have killed you,

35:22.715 --> 35:23.682
and I'm not gonna
let that happen.

35:23.716 --> 35:25.017
Going back's just as bad.

35:25.051 --> 35:26.885
First rule of combat
is survive.

35:26.920 --> 35:29.355
Greene:
Okay, let's go.

35:45.746 --> 35:48.081
Some night.
Took a big hit for this one.

35:48.116 --> 35:49.383
Yeah, it was worth it.

35:50.843 --> 35:52.437
What's gonna happen
to dad?

35:52.438 --> 35:53.904
I don't know.

35:57.776 --> 35:59.410
All right!

35:59.445 --> 36:01.546
Let's get all the kids
in the stable! Now!

36:04.349 --> 36:05.749
Hey. Hey.

36:05.784 --> 36:08.051
I got him.
I <i>got</i> him.

36:08.085 --> 36:09.719
Man:
Stay with them.

36:11.188 --> 36:12.989
No!
I'm not going!

36:13.024 --> 36:14.457
Dad!

36:15.493 --> 36:16.960
[ Gunshot ]

36:16.995 --> 36:19.129
Drop 'em!

36:21.199 --> 36:23.268
Okay, who's next?!

36:23.302 --> 36:26.104
Who's next?!

36:42.755 --> 36:42.788
What about me, Dan?

36:45.724 --> 36:47.425
You gonna shoot me, too?

36:47.459 --> 36:49.961
Only if I have to.

36:51.063 --> 36:53.130
Tom...

36:53.165 --> 36:54.933
So what's the next step
in this plan of yours?

36:54.967 --> 36:56.167
'Cause I was
thinking maybe...

36:57.536 --> 36:58.703
[ Grunts ]

37:05.878 --> 37:07.012
You okay?

37:07.046 --> 37:08.080
Yeah.

37:08.114 --> 37:09.782
Yeah, I'm okay.

37:09.817 --> 37:11.951
Did you know
they were waiting for us?

37:11.985 --> 37:13.519
I hoped.

37:15.489 --> 37:17.123
Wasn't sure
you were gonna show up.

37:17.157 --> 37:18.958
I almost didn't.

37:18.993 --> 37:21.694
Dad!

37:21.729 --> 37:23.863
Told you to <i>send</i> the cavalry,
not come with them.

37:31.038 --> 37:32.839
What do you want to do
about <i>them?</i>

37:32.873 --> 37:34.307
We'll take their weapons,

37:34.342 --> 37:37.643
but I don't see bringing these
people back to the 2nd Mass.

37:42.916 --> 37:45.551
You people...

37:45.586 --> 37:47.987
You can go or you can stay --
I don't really give a damn.

37:48.021 --> 37:50.657
But if I find that you've been
dealing with the Skitters again,

37:50.691 --> 37:52.058
I'll kill every last one
of you.

37:52.092 --> 37:55.028
Thanks for coming back
for us.

37:56.898 --> 37:58.865
You did really good.

38:02.069 --> 38:04.904
[ Baby crying ]

38:04.939 --> 38:06.839
Charlotte,
how can you be hungry again?

38:06.874 --> 38:11.176
Why is it I always get the seat
next to the crying baby?

38:12.946 --> 38:14.747
Show's over, creep.

38:14.781 --> 38:17.316
That wasn't for you.

38:17.351 --> 38:18.885
[ Chuckles ]

38:20.654 --> 38:24.456
Congratulations
on a successful delivery.

38:24.491 --> 38:26.125
Weaver did
most of the work.

38:26.159 --> 38:28.627
After that, it was just
your average childbirth

38:28.661 --> 38:30.195
in a high-school
chem lab.

38:30.230 --> 38:31.430
Sarah was great.

38:31.464 --> 38:33.599
Baby Charlotte
is beautiful.

38:33.633 --> 38:37.102
10 fingers, 10 toes.
[ Chuckles ]

38:37.136 --> 38:39.972
I always loved
that sound.

38:40.006 --> 38:41.674
Yeah, I'm <i>fine,</i>
<i>by the way.</i>

38:41.708 --> 38:42.808
He'll limp,

38:42.843 --> 38:44.344
but he'll live.

38:46.614 --> 38:49.082
You could have
kept running.

38:49.117 --> 38:51.218
Probably <i>should</i> have.

38:51.253 --> 38:55.489
Probably still will,
given half the chance.

38:55.524 --> 38:57.058
Well, until you do,
the kitchen's short-handed.

38:58.927 --> 39:00.294
I guess I'm back
where I started.

39:00.329 --> 39:02.563
Consider yourself lucky.

39:04.766 --> 39:07.167
[ Birds chirping ]

39:13.608 --> 39:16.477
Mike was a good man,
good father.

39:16.512 --> 39:21.149
I could tell from being around
him how much he loved Rick.

39:21.184 --> 39:25.421
Like all of us here today,
he was faced with a decision.

39:25.455 --> 39:29.058
He could have run
and saved himself.

39:29.093 --> 39:30.493
But instead...

39:32.463 --> 39:37.066
...He stood his ground
and fought for us.

39:37.101 --> 39:40.169
I'm gonna miss him.

39:40.204 --> 39:41.804
We're gonna miss him.

39:46.910 --> 39:48.911
Captain.

39:48.945 --> 39:50.579
You go ahead.

39:59.055 --> 40:02.524
Tom: If this was
a proper military funeral,

40:02.559 --> 40:05.561
we'd have somebody
playing "Taps."

40:05.595 --> 40:10.199
It's a bugler's song
from the Civil War

40:10.233 --> 40:12.668
used to signify
the end of a day's work.

40:12.703 --> 40:15.405
And in a way, it's a lullaby,

40:15.439 --> 40:18.475
to tell soldiers that...

40:18.509 --> 40:22.478
All was well
and that it was safe to rest.

40:24.582 --> 40:26.850
So rest easy, Mike.

40:29.587 --> 40:31.387
We'll take it from here.

40:51.809 --> 41:00.351
♪ And our eyes at last
shall see him ♪

41:00.385 --> 41:02.887
♪ through his own... ♪

41:02.922 --> 41:05.991
Clayton told his Skitter friends
that he'd secured our kids.

41:06.025 --> 41:08.193
That ought to buy us
a couple of days.

41:10.496 --> 41:13.765
Should never have
let them go.

41:13.800 --> 41:17.269
It was the best option,
given what we knew.

41:17.304 --> 41:19.939
Next time,
I'll trust my instincts.

41:19.973 --> 41:26.579
♪ ...Our lord, in heaven above ♪

41:29.616 --> 41:33.352
I don't understand...

41:33.386 --> 41:37.256
How people could kill
each other.

41:37.290 --> 41:39.959
Sorry about your dad.

41:39.994 --> 41:42.095
Why?

41:42.129 --> 41:44.598
Killing's
in their nature.

41:46.467 --> 41:47.801
<i>Their</i> nature?

41:47.835 --> 41:50.737
Humans.

41:50.772 --> 41:53.040
<i>We</i> would never kill
one of our own.

41:55.543 --> 41:57.644
You should
understand that.

